</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uglorianafrostglitter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gloriana Frostglitter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1344<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/30/02 10:56:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3220.topic&index=85>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I guess it was inevitable...</span><hr size=1> Heh, I actually did know that Gloriana was a nickname of Queen Elizabeth I (being a well-educated reader of Elizabethean bodice rippers *cough*)  That, however, does not make me a hypocrite.  To quote myself:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I hate stupid phrase/real world terms names in EQ<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To be more specific, I dislike stupid phrase names like &quot;Stabbed Indaback&quot; or real word terms, like dynomite or percoset.  I actually kinda like obscure literary/historical/mythological names like Rian (from one of my favorite books by Guy Gavriel Kay) or Morkeleb (of which there are two on our server, from a great book by Barbra Hambly).  I also have a high elf cleric, Amalthea (the goat that fed Zeus as a baby as well as the name of the unicorn in the Last Unicorn) and a mage named Elektra (Greek mythology).<br>
<br>
I don't feel the former names belong in a fantasy setting, while the latter seem to fit perfectly.  I have never petitioned a name (not even Fellatiolicious!).  Stupid names like that don't &quot;offend&quot; me, they are just eye-rollingly lame. <br>
<br>
Back to the name, Gloriana. I had actually never done a websearch on the name, it seems to have been a name better suited for a bard, since most of the web matches involve choral groups, not Queens of England.  In fact, there are 8910 web matches for the word, &quot;Gloriana,&quot; are they *ALL* related to Queen Elizabeth I or is it just a really pretty sounding name? <br>
<br>
Unlike Gandalf which is soley linked to the novels by Tolkein, I believe Gloriana is not in violation of the naming policy since it is currently used by several organizations, individuals like a professor of literature at Carnegie and even a brand of thread which have nothing to do with the first Queen Elizabeth.  Did all of those choral groups, florists, bookstores, boats and dressmaker's shears (!) get the name from the same place? Doubful really, it seems as common as if I had named myself Cindy or Marie!<br>
  <br>
As far as ad hominem attacks go, you seem to fit the bill completely, you can't argue with me without calling me a &quot;petty bitch,&quot; attacking ME not my argument. When arguing with Arikel, you couldn't just stick to his points and counter with your own, you had to call him &quot;dumb.&quot;  Attacking the person, not the argument is pretty classic ad hominem.  It was pretty funny to come back to see Arikel and Carathos debating you into a corner, nice work guys!<br>
<br>
PS Thanks for inspiring me to do a web search, I found the most gorgeous poem!<br>
<br>
To Gloriana - Vachel Lindsay (An American poet who composed this during WWI, probably not about Queen Elizabeth I!)<br>
<br>
GIRL with the burning golden eyes, <br>
And red-bird song, and snowy throat: <br>
I bring you gold and silver moons, <br>
And diamond stars, and mists that float. <br>
I bring you moons and snowy clouds, <br>
I bring you prarie skies to-night <br>
To feebly praise your golden eyes <br>
And red-bird song, and throat so white.<br>
<br>
I think that might be my new sig!<br>
<br>
And finally, my favorite quote from Queen Elizabeth I to help give you some confidence to continue your faltering debate:<br>
<br>
`Fain would I climb, yet I fear to fall.' - written on glass by Sir Walter Raleigh in view of the Queen<br>
<br>
`If thy heart fails thee, climb not at all.' - her answer<br>
<br>
